The defendant Jesus I. Rangel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Aggravated Battery [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(6).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Jesus I. Rangel in court with attorney John H. Wallace. Defendant Jesus I. Rangel in custody. David R. Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
3:33 p.m.  Court calls the case. 

Atty Knaapen states the appearances. 
Court and both counsel have received the PSI.  

State has complied with Victim Notification Statutes.

Atty Knaapen makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Atty Wallace makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Defendant makes statements to the Court. 

BY THE COURT: 
Serve 6 years in prison with 3 years initial confinement followed by 3 years extended supervision. 
Concurrent to any other sentence he is currently serving.
146 days credit. 
No contact with the victims, Daniel Sanchez or Steven Solis, their immediate family, residences or places of employment.
No contact with Eric Constante, Frank Martinez, Austin Ortiz and Angelo Garcia.
No contact with any known or reported gang members.
Maintain absolute sobriety.
Do not possess or consume alcohol or be on premises where alcohol is served/sold as its primary business except within scope of your employment.
Do not possess/consume controlled substances without a valid prescription and be taken according to the prescription. 
Complete an AODA & comply with treatment recommendations.  DOC can accept any assessment he has had while in the prison system if deemed appropriate.
Comply with any other assessment, treatment or programming as deemed appropriate by COMPAS assessment and DOC.
Sign releases of information for offenders assessment or treatment, also any pharmacy for prescription medications.
Use only one pharmacy and notify agent. 
Pay all court ordered obligations in full 90 days prior to discharge.
Pay restitution of $18,983.20.  Joint & Sereral with co-defendants. 
Pay costs. 
Pay 10% restitution surcharge.
Pay DNA surcharge. 
Obtain and maintain fulltime employment and/or schooling or a combination of both equal to fulltime.
To pursue fulltime employment to pay the restitution.  Education beyond that is on his own time or he can do fulltime education if he has paid the restitution in full.
Provide a DNA sample if not already done so. 
Court finds, due to the defendants prior work record, the defendant should be able to pay the restitution and DNA surcharge. 
Any restitution and costs be taken out of 25% of prison funds.  Victims are to be paid first. 
Not eligible for CIP or SAP programs. 

Atty Wallace asks that the defendant be allowed to keep the PSI. 
Court denies the request.  A copy is kept with his social worker but the defendant is not allowed to have a copy for himself.  Atty Wallace may keep the PSI in his file confidentially.
